text: hi everyone funthony runtano here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new parkay
quartz record sympathy for life this is
a brand new lp from new york rock outfit
parquet courts the highly anticipated
follow-up to the band's 2018 record wide
awake where they brought together dance
grooves protest chants and indie
aesthetics for one of the best lps of
the decade i'm sorry so of course i was
excited to hear this album especially
considering how good some of the singles
were there's walking at a downtown pace
which is more or less in the same vein
as many cuts off of wide awake it's a
driving post-punky rocker with huge
rhythms huge drums and lead vocals that
reflect on the fragility of
everyday life and modern society in the
pandemic era with lyrics about
cherishing crowds and saying you'd be
surprised what you could learn to lose
the whole track rages against the threat
of extinction then there's homo sapien
which i think exists in pretty
comfortable territory for the band as
well but calls back more to the garage
rock influences that were prominent on
the band's earlier records even
sunbathing animal the whole track is a
rowdy collision of
humanity's primal urges and our love of
modern uh technological luxuries with
great rifts gritty production and
animalistic group vocals what's not to
like then there were some songs teasing
toward this record that broke
expectations a bit black widow spider is
an attempt at an eerie garage and psych
number with some sort of surreal lyrics
to boot the fuzzy riffs and strange
sound effects that float around the mix
are cool but i think generally for this
record this is a pretty weak vocal
performance from andrew to the point
where the singing does come across a bit
awkward then the limited edition vinyl
only single plant life miraculously made
it onto this lp which sees the band
flirting more with synths and
electronics in sort of an alternative
dance direction lots of atmosphere lots
of delays lots of groove a touch of
david byrne vibes as well especially on
the spoken word bits the track overall
is more chill and calculated than it is
blood pumping and i hope that's not a
disappointment for fans because i do
think it is a well crafted piece of
dance music with some great builds so
there's those tracks there but like
these teasers
sort of forecast the rest of sympathy
for life is a mixed bag and doesn't
really bring the thematic or aesthetic
focus of their last record even human
performance or sunbathing animal maybe
at this point parque quartz is hitting a
transitional moment or feeling a little
restless in their sound and looking to
shake things up of course plant life is
not the only song on this record to
bring more synthesizers and electronics
there's marathon of anger which is a
very spacious piece of psychedelic funk
whose lyrics very clearly reference the
change in energy that new york
experienced amidst the george floyd
protests but ultimately the vibe and the
energy of the track doesn't really push
beyond that of a simmer so while i like
the picture the track paints overall as
a song it's kind of forgettable then
there's just shadows which is a number
in three four whose stiff grooves and
strain vocals are stale on impact i'm
amazed it drags on for about four
minutes application apparatus sees
parque quartz giving a somewhat novel
and post punk inspired take on
industrial music there's a thin spacey
throbbing gristle s quality to some of
the noises and glitches and sound
effects that color the mix it is a
creatively tense instrumental with these
cycling kind of sour lead vocals whose
lyrics paint this picture of a
regimented authoritarian kind of
algorithmically guided war-torn world
it's smart it's ominous i like the angle
it's taking conceptually but as a song i
don't really get too much out of it so
the choppy experiments on this record up
until this point are one thing but then
there's the last leg which in my opinion
sees the band really beginning to lose
momentum the title track is jammy yes
but very low impact on all fronts
vocally lyrically instrumentally i don't
know whether to dance or fall asleep to
this one then zoom out feels like a
bizarro version of the grooves and
chants that
colored so many tracks from wide awake
but now with less to say
not as catchy and some kooky banjo licks
going on in the right channel that
don't quite hit the basic elements are
there but it feels like there's really
no chemistry going on between all of
them then trullo brings more aimless
grooves with these mildly eccentric and
strange noises kind of orbiting the beat
here i suppose there's potential to this
track but the performance is so
underwhelming it's hard to really get
locked in the closer is a really tender
and dejected finish for the lp some of
the melodic freezing on the vocals
reminds me of the closer to the band's
last record tenderness i'm not saying
the tracks are connected especially with
the lyrics on this one being so much
more i guess focused on love but it is
something to see the band's last lp end
in i guess such a joyous way where
the energy is very much like overcoming
nihilism overcoming negativity uh
meanwhile there seems to be like very
little hope found in the final moments
of this lp and while the tune isn't
strong the emotions are potent and there
are some ingenious lyrics woven into
this one i love this line i'd rather be
stuffed with straw than made of tin
which i think says a lot about being
mindless as opposed to heartless you
know given the wizard of oz lore there
and while i don't love the song i guess
it does put a bow on
the gloominess that
colors so many songs on this lp which
ultimately is fine i don't really mind
the emotional change or the stylistic
change this record brings to the table i
guess what i wish is it made that change
more boldly and concretely because some
of the most standout moments on this lp
are tracks that sound like they could
have been from the last record overall i
think it's great the band is continuing
to try new things and push forward it's
just that the songs that seem least
likely for parker courts on this record
are often the ones that have the least
inspiration on the songwriting front and
the least amount of charm feeling a
strong five to a light six on this one
